message: Hey, I know you're feeling like you're the only one going through this, but seriously, you're not. Everyone struggles with stuff sometimes, especially now. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but trust me, they don't. It's more common than you think, and you're definitely not alone.
reflection: I remember when my parents were fighting a lot, I felt like my family was the only one dealing with that kind of stuff. It was so embarrassing and I didn't want anyone to know. message: Hey, I know it feels like you're the only one going through this, but you're really not. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially when things get tough with school or friends or whatever. It's way more common than people let on, and it doesn't mean anything is wrong with you. We're all just trying to figure things out, and it's okay to not be okay sometimes.
reflection: I remember when I didn't make the varsity soccer team freshman year. I felt like everyone else was way better than me and that I was the only one who didn't make it. But then I talked to some older girls on JV who said they didn't make it their first year either, and it made me feel a lot better knowing that it happens to other people too. It wasn't just me being a total failure.

I felt like I was the only one dealing with that kinda instability, and it was super embarrassing. But then I heard about other kids whose parents were going through stuff too, or who had to stay with other family for different reasons. Knowing that other people were in similar situations made me feel less like an outcast.

Knowing that other people have been there could make me feel less like I'm the only one who's messed up.

reflection: I remember before tryouts for the soccer team, I was so nervous I thought I was gonna throw up. I felt like everyone else was super confident and I was the only one freaking out. But then I talked to some of the other girls, and they were just as nervous as me, even the really good ones. Knowing that made me feel a little better, like it wasn't just me who was a mess. It helped me calm down a little and actually focus on the game.
takeaway: I think the biggest thing is just remembering that everyone struggles, even if they don't show it. So, if I'm feeling down, I shouldn't beat myself up about it because it's probably something other people have gone through too. reflection: I remember when I first came out as bi, I felt super alone and like no one else understood. I thought everyone else had it figured out and I was the only one confused. It made me feel way less alone and more normal, even though it felt like a huge deal at first.

message: Hey man, I know you feel like you're the only one going through this, but trust me, you're not. Everyone deals with crap, especially now. It might seem like everyone else is fine, but they're probably just hiding it. You're not alone, and it doesn't mean you're weak or anything.
reflection: I remember when I first started having panic attacks, I thought I was going crazy. It felt like I was the only one whose body was betraying them like that. But then I started seeing a therapist, and she told me tons of people have anxiety, more than I realized. Knowing that didn't make the attacks go away, but it made me feel less like a total freak, y'know?

Knowing that other people felt the same way made me feel a little less alone.

message: Hey, I know things suck right now, but you're def not the only one feeling this way. Everyone struggles sometimes, even if they don't show it. It's easy to think you're alone, but trust me, there are tons of people your age going through the same stuff. Just remember that it's okay to not be okay, and it won't last forever.
reflection: After my second attempt, I felt completely isolated, like no one could understand what I was going through. It was like I was broken in a way that others weren't. But knowing that other people have also felt that desperate and have survived makes me feel a little less alone, even if it doesn't fix everything. It's like...okay, maybe I'm not as weird as I thought.
takeaway: It's important to remember that even when I feel like I'm the only one struggling, that's probably not true. Other people are going through similar stuff, and reaching out might actually help.

message: Hey, I know it feels like you're the only one going through this, but trust me, you're not. Everyone struggles, especially now. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but they don't. We're all just trying to figure things out, and it's okay to not be okay sometimes. We can get through this together, and just knowing you're not alone can make a huge difference.
reflection: After... everything that happened, I felt like nobody could understand. Like I was carrying this huge, messed-up secret, and it made me totally different from everyone else. I guess knowing that other people have gone through similar things, that it's not just me, makes it a tiny bit easier. Like, maybe I'm not a freak, just human.
takeaway: It's important to remember that everyone struggles, even if they don't show it. Just because I'm feeling like crap doesn't mean I'm broken or alone. It's just part of being human, I guess.

message: Hey, I know things are tough right now, but you're definitely not alone. Seriously, everyone struggles sometimes, even if it doesn't look like it on the outside. We all have those moments where we feel like we're the only ones dealing with something, but trust me, a lot of other teens are going through the same stuff. It's just part of growing up, I guess.
reflection: I remember when I was having a hard time with my weight. I felt like everyone else was skinny and happy, and I was the only one struggling. It made me feel super alone and self-conscious. But thinking about how other people probably feel insecure about their bodies too, it makes me feel a little less isolated. It's like, okay, I'm not the only one dealing with this, and maybe we can all just be a little kinder to ourselves.
takeaway: I guess the biggest thing is knowing that it's okay to not be okay sometimes, and that I'm probably not the only one feeling that way. Remembering that other people struggle too can make it a little easier to deal with my own stuff.

message: Hey, I know you're feeling like you're the only one going through this, but honestly, you're not. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially with stuff like school or friends. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but trust me, they don't. We're all just trying to figure things out, and it's okay to not be okay sometimes.
reflection: Okay, so last year I didn't make the varsity soccer team, and I felt like total garbage. I thought everyone else was just, like, naturally good and I was the only one who wasn't good enough. But I guess a lot of people probably get cut from teams or don't reach their goals, and maybe it doesn't mean they're terrible, just that they have to work harder or something. Knowing that other people have similar setbacks makes me feel a little less alone, I guess.
takeaway: I guess the big thing is to remember that everyone struggles, even if they don't show it. Just because I'm going through something hard doesn't mean I'm weird or alone, and it's okay to ask for help.

message: Hey, I know you're going through a lot right now, and it might feel like you're the only one, but trust me, you're not. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially as a teen. We all deal with pressure, sadness, and feeling lost. It's normal, even if it sucks. Just know that you're not alone in this.
reflection: I used to think I was the only one who didn't know what they wanted to do after high school. Everyone else seemed to have a plan, like college or a career, and I was just drifting. But then I talked to some friends, and they admitted they were just as clueless as me. Knowing that made me feel way less alone, and that it was okay to figure things out at my own pace.

message: Hey, I get it, it feels like you're the only one going through this, but trust me, you're not. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially us teens, because so much is changing. It's easy to think everyone else has it together, but they don't. So many people are feeling the same way you are right now, you're def not alone.
reflection: Okay, so there was this time after I got my third concussion playing soccer. I felt so down, like my brain was never gonna be the same, and all my friends were still playing and having fun. I thought I was the only one who felt so messed up from sports. But now I'm thinking, maybe other people have gone through the same thing, and just didn't talk about it as much. I can't be the only one who felt alone in that moment.
takeaway: I think the big thing I want to remember is that it's okay to not be okay. And just because I'm struggling doesn't mean I'm some kind of weirdo. Lots of people are going through stuff too, even if they don't show it.

message: Hey, I know things seem rough right now, and it feels like you're the only one going through it, but you're really not alone. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially teens with all the stuff we have to deal with. It doesn't make you weird or anything, it just means you're human. We'll get through this together.
reflection: I remember when my parents were fighting a lot, and I felt like no one else understood what it was like to live in a house like that. I thought everyone else had perfect families, and I was the only one dealing with the drama. But then I talked to some friends and found out their parents fought too. Knowing that I wasn't the only one made me feel a little less alone, and a little more normal.
takeaway: Just because I'm struggling doesn't mean I'm broken or weird. It just means I'm going through something, and other people probably have too. It's okay to not be okay, and it's important to remember that I'm not alone.

message: Hey, I get it. It feels like you're the only one going through stuff sometimes, but honestly, you're not. Everyone deals with their own battles, whether it's with school, friends, or family. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but trust me, they don't. We're all in this together, and it's normal to feel like crap sometimes. Don't think you're alone, because you definitely aren't.
reflection: I remember when I seriously considered attempting suicide last year. I felt so isolated and like nobody understood what I was going through. I was convinced I was the only one who ever felt that hopeless. But if I knew more people felt like that, maybe I wouldn't have felt so alone. message: Hey, I know you're going through it right now, and it probably feels like you're the only one, but you're totally not. Everyone struggles, especially during high school. It's easy to think everyone else has it figured out, but trust me, they don't. We're all just trying to survive, and a lot of us are feeling the same stuff you are right now. You're not alone.
reflection: I remember when I started feeling really down and hopeless, like nothing mattered anymore. I thought I was just broken or something, and that nobody else understood what it was like to feel so empty all the time. But then I started talking to a therapist, and I realized that tons of teens struggle with depression and suicidal thoughts. Knowing that I wasn't the only one made it a little easier to deal with, like I wasn't some weird freak.
takeaway: I guess I should remember that just because I'm feeling like crap doesn't mean I'm a freak. Other people are probably struggling too, even if they don't show it. And maybe knowing that can help me feel less alone and more willing to reach out.

message: Hey, I know things are tough right now, and it feels like you're the only one dealing with this, but you're seriously not alone. Everyone struggles sometimes, even if they don't show it. It's totally normal to feel like crap when things get hard, and so many other teens are going through the same stuff. Just know that you're not weird or broken for feeling this way.
reflection: When my parents were fighting all the time, I thought our family was the only one with that kind of drama. It felt like everyone else had perfect lives, and I was stuck in this messed-up situation by myself. But now I'm realizing that tons of other kids have parents who argue, or worse. Knowing that doesn't fix anything, but it makes me feel less like a total freak.

message: Hey, it's okay to feel like you're the only one struggling sometimes, but trust me, you're not. Everyone goes through tough stuff, especially as a teen. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but most people don't show when they are having hard times. Just remember that you're definitely not alone, and things will get better, okay?
reflection: I remember when I didn't do well in a test and I felt like I was the dumbest person in class and that everyone was smarter than me. It made me feel super alone. But knowing that other people also fail sometimes, and that test scores don't mean everything, kinda helps. Like, it's not just me who struggles, and that's... a relief.
takeaway: I think the main thing I want to remember is that it's okay to not be okay, and that everyone else is struggling too, even if they don't show it. Remembering that I'm not alone can make things less scary, so yeah, I need to remember that.

paragraph: I remember after my concussion from soccer, I felt so frustrated and isolated. I couldn't focus in school, I was always tired, and I felt like no one understood what I was going through. I thought everyone else was just fine and I was the only one struggling, but maybe other athletes have felt this way too. Knowing that it's common could've made me feel less like I was completely alone and going crazy.

reflection: I remember when I got that concussion playing football. I felt super down and out, like I was the only one who couldn't get back in the game. But then I talked to some older guys on the team who had been through the same thing. Knowing that they understood and had recovered made me feel a lot less alone and more hopeful that I'd get back to normal too.

It made me feel less weird about it, knowing I wasn't the only one obsessed with that stuff.

message: Hey, I know things suck right now, but you're not the only one feeling like this. Seriously, everyone struggles sometimes, even if they don't show it. It's normal to feel down or stressed when things get tough, and it doesn't mean there's something wrong with you. Just remember that you're not alone, and things will get better eventually.
reflection: After my suicide attempt, I felt like a total freak. I was convinced that no one could ever understand what I was going through. message: Hey, don't feel like you're the only one going through this. Everyone struggles sometimes, especially with school and stuff. It might seem like everyone else has it together, but trust me, they don't. We're all just trying to figure things out, and it's normal to feel down or stressed. You're def not alone.
reflection: Last year, I was super stressed about tryouts for the basketball team. I thought everyone else was way more confident than me, and that I was the only one freaking out. But then I talked to some of the other guys, and they were just as nervous. It made me feel better knowing that I wasn't the only one feeling the pressure, and that it was actually pretty normal.
takeaway: It's important to remember that everyone struggles sometimes, and you're not alone in feeling down or stressed. Knowing that others go through similar stuff can make things feel less isolating and more manageable.

message: Hey, I know things are tough right now, but you're definitely not the only one feeling this way. Seriously, so many teens go through similar struggles, especially with all the pressure we're under. It doesn't mean anything is wrong with you, it just means you're human. We can talk about it if you want, or just hang out and take your mind off things.
reflection: I remember when I was trying out for the basketball team freshman year. I was so nervous and felt like everyone else was way more confident than me. I messed up a few times and was convinced I was the only one struggling that badly. Thinking about it now, I bet a lot of other girls were just as anxious, even if they didn't show it. It would have been easier if I'd known I wasn't alone in feeling like I was bombing.
takeaway: It's easy to feel like you're the only one struggling, but remembering that other people go through similar stuff can make things a little less overwhelming. Knowing you're not alone can help you get through it.
